.TH "oans" "8" "July 2026" "oans 1.3.0" "System Manager\[cq]s Manual"
.SH NAME
\f[CR]oans\f[R] \[em] find duplicate data in files and share it with the
kernel\[cq]s deduplication ioctl.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]oans\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]file\f[R]\&...
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]oans\f[R] \f[B]\-d\f[R] [\f[B]\-r\f[R]]
\f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]=\f[I]FILE\f[R] \f[I]file\f[R]\&...
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]oans\f[R] \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]=\f[I]FILE\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]oans\f[R] {\f[B]\-\-stats\f[R] | \f[B]\-\-history\f[R] |
\f[B]\-\-json\f[R] | \f[B]\-L\f[R]}
\f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]=\f[I]FILE\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]oans\f[R] \f[B]\-R\f[R] \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]=\f[I]FILE\f[R]
\f[I]file\f[R]\&...
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]oans\f[R] \f[B]\-\-autotune\f[R] \f[I]file\f[R]\&...
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[CR]oans\f[R] finds regions of identical data across a set of files
and, on request, asks the kernel to make them share storage \[em]
reclaiming the duplicated space without changing what any file contains.
It works on \f[B]btrfs\f[R] and \f[B]xfs\f[R], the Linux filesystems
that support reflink/dedupe.
.PP
Deduplication is performed with the kernel\[cq]s
\f[B]\f[CB]FIDEDUPERANGE\f[B]\f[R] ioctl, which \f[B]byte\-for\-byte
compares\f[R] every candidate range and locks the files while it does
so.
Because the kernel \[em] not \f[CR]oans\f[R] \[em] moves the data, a bug
in \f[CR]oans\f[R] can only waste work or miss a dedupe; it can never
corrupt your files.
.PP
Given a list of files and directories, \f[CR]oans\f[R] reads them,
hashes their contents on an extent basis, and groups extents whose
hashes match.
Without \f[B]\-d\f[R] it only \f[I]reports\f[R] what it would dedupe (a
dry run); with \f[B]\-d\f[R] it submits the matches to the kernel and
prints how much space was reclaimed.
.PP
\f[CR]oans\f[R] scales to large trees by keeping its hashes in a
\f[B]hashfile\f[R] (see \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]), an SQLite database it
updates incrementally: on a re\-run it re\-hashes only the files whose
size or mtime changed, and skips extents that are already shared.
The hashfile is \f[B]self\-describing\f[R] \[em] it records the options,
paths, and excludes of each run \[em] so a scheduled job need only name
it (see \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R] and the \f[I]EXAMPLES\f[R]).
.PP
\f[CR]oans\f[R] is a fork of \f[CR]duperemove\f[R];
\f[CR]make install\f[R] also installs a \f[CR]duperemove\f[R] symlink so
existing scripts keep working.
Its hashfiles are branded and are not interchangeable with upstream
duperemove\[cq]s (each rebuilds its own; they are only caches, so
nothing is lost).
.SH MODES OF OPERATION
\f[B]Read\-only (default).\f[R] Without \f[B]\-d\f[R], \f[CR]oans\f[R]
reads, hashes, and prints the duplicate extents it found \[em] useful
for previewing what a dedupe run would do.
Nothing on disk is changed.
It does not concern itself with how an extent is stored (compressed,
already shared, mid\-I/O); in dedupe mode the kernel handles those
details.
.PP
\f[B]Deduplicating (\-d).\f[R] The same read\-hash\-compare step, but
matching extents are submitted to the kernel for sharing.
Extents that are already shared are detected up front and skipped, so
repeated runs over a mostly\-stable tree are cheap.
A summary of the space reclaimed is printed at the end (see
\f[I]OUTPUT\f[R]).
.PP
\f[B]Report and maintenance modes.\f[R] \f[B]\-\-stats\f[R],
\f[B]\-\-history\f[R], \f[B]\-\-json\f[R], \f[B]\-L\f[R], \f[B]\-R\f[R],
and \f[B]\-\-autotune\f[R] each inspect or maintain a hashfile and then
exit without scanning for dupes.
The first four open the hashfile \f[B]read\-only\f[R]; see
\f[I]NOTES\f[R] for running them alongside an active \f[CR]oans\f[R].
.SH OPTIONS
The non\-option arguments are the \f[I]files\f[R] and
\f[I]directories\f[R] to scan, or a single hyphen (\f[B]\-\f[R]) to read
the list from standard input, one path per line.
Naming a directory scans the regular files directly inside it; add
\f[B]\-r\f[R] to recurse.
.SS Operation
.TP
\f[B]\-d\f[R]
Deduplicate: submit matching extents to the kernel
(\f[B]btrfs\f[R]/\f[B]xfs\f[R] only).
Without \f[B]\-d\f[R], \f[CR]oans\f[R] performs a read\-only dry run and
only reports.
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R]
Recurse into subdirectories of any directory argument.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R]=\f[I]FILE\f[R]
Store hashes in \f[I]FILE\f[R] (an SQLite database) instead of memory.
This is the recommended way to run \f[CR]oans\f[R] on anything larger
than a handful of files: it keeps the memory footprint modest and makes
runs \f[B]incremental\f[R] and \f[B]resumable\f[R].
.RS
.PP
If \f[I]FILE\f[R] does not exist it is created.
If it exists, \f[CR]oans\f[R] compares the stored size/mtime of each
recorded path and re\-hashes only what changed.
Paths that no longer exist on disk are pruned automatically (by
existence, so files merely outside the paths scanned this run are kept);
the database is compacted once enough of it is free.
.PP
New files are added to the hashfile only when they are reachable from
the \f[I]file\f[R] arguments, so normally you pass the same paths and
\f[B]\-r\f[R] each run.
Discovery is efficient and visits each file once, even ones already
stored.
.PP
Because the hashfile also records the run\[cq]s options, paths, and
\f[B]\-\-exclude\f[R] patterns, you need not repeat them:
\f[B]\f[CB]oans \-\-hashfile=FILE\f[B]\f[R] with no \f[I]file\f[R]
arguments \f[B]replays the last run\f[R] (any other options on that
command line are ignored).
If none of the stored paths still exist \f[CR]oans\f[R] refuses rather
than prune every entry \[em] guarding against, e.g., an unmounted drive
\[em] while individually missing paths are skipped with a warning.
.PP
When deduping from a hashfile, files that have not changed since they
were last deduped are skipped.
.RE
.SS Scan tuning
.TP
\f[B]\-b\f[R] \f[I]SIZE\f[R]
Block size used when reading and hashing file data.
Default \f[B]128K\f[R]; accepted range \f[B]4K\f[R]\[en]\f[B]1M\f[R]
(suffixes \f[CR]K\f[R]/\f[CR]M\f[R] accepted).
Smaller blocks can surface more sub\-extent matches when partial
matching is enabled (\f[B]\-\-dedupe\-options=partial\f[R]) but cost
more CPU and a larger hashfile; larger blocks fragment less.
Most users never need to change this.
.TP
\f[B]\-B\f[R] \f[I]N\f[R], \f[B]\-\-batchsize\f[R]=\f[I]N\f[R]
Run the dedupe phase after every \f[I]N\f[R] newly scanned files instead
of once at the end.
This caps memory use on large data sets and when partial matching is
enabled, at a small cost to multithreading efficiency.
Default \f[B]1024\f[R], a good value for extent\-based dedupe; drop it
toward \f[B]1\f[R] when working on very large files (VM images,
backups).
.TP
\f[B]\-m\f[R] \f[I]SIZE\f[R], \f[B]\-\-min\-filesize\f[R]=\f[I]SIZE\f[R]
Skip regular files smaller than \f[I]SIZE\f[R] bytes (suffixes
\f[CR]K\f[R]/\f[CR]M\f[R]/\f[CR]G\f[R] accepted).
Trees full of tiny files scan much faster this way, since such files
rarely dedupe usefully.
Default \f[B]1\f[R], which skips only empty files.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-skip\-zeroes\f[R]
Detect and skip all\-zero blocks while reading.
Speeds up scanning of sparse or zero\-filled data, at the cost of not
deduplicating runs of zeroes.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-exclude\f[R]=\f[I]PATTERN\f[R]
Exclude matching files and directories from the scan \[em] handy for
skipping snapshot mounts or caches.
A \f[I]PATTERN\f[R] without a leading \f[CR]/\f[R] is matched relative
to the current directory.
Because the shell also expands globs, quote the pattern,
e.g.\ \f[CR]oans \-\-exclude \[dq]/srv/media/tmp/*\[dq] /srv/media\f[R].
May be given multiple times.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-dedupe\-options\f[R]=\f[I]opt\f[R][,\f[I]opt\f[R]\&...]
Comma\-separated switches that alter \f[I]what\f[R] gets deduplicated.
Prefix an option with \f[B]no\f[R] to turn it off.
.RS
.TP
\f[B][no]same\f[R]
Allow deduplicating extents that live within the \f[I]same\f[R] file.
Default \f[B]on\f[R].
.TP
\f[B][no]partial\f[R]
Also compare \f[I]portions\f[R] of extents (block\-level matching),
finding dedupe that pure extent matching misses.
Powerful but CPU\-intensive and larger on disk; pair it with
\f[B]\-\-batchsize\f[R] to bound memory.
Default \f[B]off\f[R].
(This path is under active development and its semantics may change.)
.TP
\f[B][no]only_whole_files\f[R]
Restrict dedupe to entire, byte\-identical files, disabling both
extent\- and block\-level matching.
The hashfile is smaller and some steps are faster, but less duplication
is found.
Default \f[B]off\f[R].
.RE
.SS Threads
.TP
\f[B]\-\-io\-threads\f[R]=\f[I]N\f[R]
Number of threads for the I/O\-bound stages (directory walk, file
hashing, dedupe).
By default \f[CR]oans\f[R] inspects the scan target\[cq]s backing
storage and chooses automatically: the host CPU count capped at
\f[B]8\f[R] for non\-rotational disks (SSD/NVMe) or unknown media; fewer
for a single spinning disk (seek\-bound); and roughly two per device for
a multi\-device btrfs pool, still capped at 8.
Run with \f[B]\-v\f[R] to see the detected storage and the value chosen.
A stored \f[B]\-\-autotune\f[R] result, if present, is used in
preference to the heuristic.
Passing \f[I]N\f[R] explicitly disables all of this and uses \f[I]N\f[R]
verbatim.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-cpu\-threads\f[R]=\f[I]N\f[R]
Number of threads for the CPU\-bound duplicate\-extent\-finding stage.
Default is the host CPU count capped at \f[B]8\f[R]; an explicit
\f[I]N\f[R] overrides the cap.
.SS Reporting and maintenance (each exits after running)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-stats\f[R]
Print a summary of the hashfile and exit: its format and identity, the
stored scan configuration a bare replay would use, how many files and
hashes it holds, the total logical data tracked, and the whole\-file
duplication it records (duplicate groups and their logical duplicate
volume).
That volume is a logical figure \[em] it is already shared on disk if
you have run a dedupe, so check \f[B]\-\-history\f[R] for bytes actually
freed and \f[CR]compsize\f[R](8) for on\-disk usage.
Requires \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-history\f[R]
Print the run history recorded in the hashfile and exit: the number of
runs, the total space reclaimed over their lifetime, and a timeline of
recent runs (date, reclaimed bytes, elapsed time, files hashed, and
whether each was a dedupe or a scan).
One row is appended automatically per run.
Requires \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-json\f[R]
Print the hashfile\[cq]s current metrics as a flat JSON object \[em]
files, hashes, logical bytes, duplicate groups, reclaimable bytes, plus
lifetime run\-history totals \[em] then exit.
Intended for scripting and dashboards (pipe to \f[CR]jq\f[R], Telegraf,
a node_exporter textfile).
\f[CR]reclaimable_logical_bytes\f[R] is a logical upper bound; real disk
freed is smaller on a compressed filesystem.
Requires \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-L\f[R]
List every file tracked in the hashfile and exit; \f[B]\-v\f[R] adds
per\-file detail.
Requires \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-R\f[R] \f[I]file\f[R]\&...
Remove the named paths from the hashfile and exit; a single \f[B]\-\f[R]
reads the list from standard input.
Requires \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
(Deleted files are also pruned automatically on the next scan;
\f[B]\-R\f[R] is for removing paths that still exist.)
.TP
\f[B]\-\-autotune\f[R]
Measure the fastest \f[B]\-\-io\-threads\f[R] for this machine and exit.
\f[CR]oans\f[R] reads and hashes a bounded sample of the given tree at
several thread counts, dropping the page cache between trials (run as
\f[B]root\f[R] for meaningful cold\-read numbers on spinning disks), and
prints a throughput table with the winner.
Directories are always sampled recursively \[em] the sample is about the
storage, not the \f[B]\-r\f[R] flag.
With \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R] the winning value \f[I]and\f[R] the scan
configuration are stored, so \f[CR]\-\-autotune\f[R] doubles as
one\-time setup: a later bare \f[CR]oans \-\-hashfile=FILE\f[R] replays
it, using the tuned thread count unless you pass an explicit
\f[B]\-\-io\-threads\f[R].
This is the hardware\-measured counterpart to the storage heuristic and
the reliable way to tune a NAS or disk array.
Sample bounds are controlled by the \f[CR]DUPEREMOVE_AUTOTUNE_*\f[R]
variables (see \f[I]ENVIRONMENT\f[R]).
.SS Output and information
.TP
\f[B]\-q\f[R], \f[B]\-\-quiet\f[R]
Quiet: print only errors and a one\-line dedupe summary.
Suppresses the live progress display and the human summary block.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
Verbose: restore the per\-group dedupe listing that is hidden by default
in favor of the progress bar, and show the detected storage / chosen
thread count.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-progress=json\f[R]
Stream machine\-readable progress instead of the interactive display,
for monitoring scheduled or non\-interactive runs.
One newline\-delimited JSON object is written to \f[B]standard
error\f[R] per phase (and about once a second), ending with a
\f[CR]{\[dq]event\[dq]:\[dq]done\[dq], ...}\f[R] line; standard output
is unchanged (so the \f[CR]net change in shared extents\f[R] line and
the human summary still appear there).
Works whether or not standard output is a terminal.
.RS
.PP
Each line is a self\-contained object.
During scanning:
\f[CR]{\[dq]phase\[dq]:\[dq]scanning\[dq],\[dq]elapsed_sec\[dq]:2.1,\[dq]files_examined\[dq]:48120,\[dq]files_to_hash\[dq]:12340}\f[R];
during hashing: \f[CR]\[dq]phase\[dq]:\[dq]hashing\[dq]\f[R] with
\f[CR]files\f[R], \f[CR]files_total\f[R], \f[CR]bytes\f[R],
\f[CR]bytes_total\f[R], and, once measurable, \f[CR]bytes_per_sec\f[R]
and \f[CR]eta_sec\f[R]; during dedupe:
\f[CR]\[dq]phase\[dq]:\[dq]dedupe\[dq]\f[R] with \f[CR]groups\f[R],
\f[CR]groups_total\f[R], \f[CR]work_done_bytes\f[R],
\f[CR]work_total_bytes\f[R], \f[CR]reclaimed_bytes\f[R], the current
\f[CR]activity\f[R], and \f[CR]eta_sec\f[R].
\f[CR]work_total_bytes\f[R] is the total kernel byte\-verify volume the
phase will do (computed exactly up front) and \f[CR]work_done_bytes\f[R]
counts up to it; these drive the smooth dedupe progress bar and are
emitted raw (never clamped backwards), so \f[CR]work_done_bytes\f[R] is
non\-decreasing and reaches \f[CR]work_total_bytes\f[R] on the last
dedupe line.
The final line is
\f[CR]{\[dq]event\[dq]:\[dq]done\[dq],\[dq]elapsed_sec\[dq]:...,\[dq]files_scanned\[dq]:...,\[dq]groups_deduped\[dq]:...,\[dq]reclaimed_bytes\[dq]:...}\f[R].
Fields that are not yet known (an ETA, a rate) are omitted; a consumer
reading a line at a time can ignore any line that is not valid JSON.
.PP
Combine with \f[B]\-q\f[R] to silence the human stdout too, e.g.
\f[CR]oans \-qd \-\-progress=json \-\-hashfile=FILE /srv/data 2>progress.jsonl\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]\-\-no\-color\f[R]
Disable colored output.
Color is also disabled automatically when standard output is not a
terminal or when the \f[CR]NO_COLOR\f[R] environment variable is set.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-debug\f[R]
Print debug messages; implies \f[B]\-v\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-version\f[R]
Print the \f[CR]oans\f[R] version and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Print a short usage summary and exit.
(For the full reference, read this manual page: \f[B]man 8 oans\f[R].)
.SH OUTPUT
A dedupe run ends with a summary such as:
.IP
.EX
Summary
  Reclaimed      133.1 GiB across 164872 groups
  Elapsed        92.1s
  Already shared 350708 files skipped (no work needed)
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Reclaimed\f[R] is the disk space actually freed: for a group of
\f[I]N\f[R] identical copies, \f[CR]oans\f[R] keeps one physical copy
and frees the other \f[I]N\f[R]−1, so this is the honest bytes\-freed
figure, not an inflated count.
\f[B]Already shared\f[R] counts files skipped because their storage was
already shared.
If some destinations could not be deduped (their data changed since the
scan, or the kernel refused), a \f[B]Not deduped\f[R] line reports the
counts; re\-run with \f[B]\-v\f[R] for detail.
.PP
When standard output is not a terminal, or under \f[B]\-q\f[R],
\f[CR]oans\f[R] also prints a stable machine\-readable line:
.IP
.EX
Comparison of extent info shows a net change in shared extents of: N
.EE
.PP
This \f[I]N\f[R] is a lower\-level fiemap diagnostic \[em] the change in
bytes the filesystem reports as shared \[em] and counts the surviving
copy as shared too, so for pairs it is about twice \f[B]Reclaimed\f[R].
Scripts that parsed this line from upstream duperemove continue to work.
.PP
On a \f[B]compressed\f[R] btrfs, \f[B]Reclaimed\f[R] is a
\f[I]logical\f[R] figure: dedupe shares logical extents but frees
compressed blocks, so the real on\-disk saving is smaller, roughly by
your compression ratio.
For ground truth compare \f[CR]compsize\f[R] \f[B]Disk Usage\f[R] before
and after a run (its \f[B]Referenced\f[R] total should not change \[em]
proof that no data was lost).
.SH EXAMPLES
Dedupe a small directory tree in place (no hashfile; fine for a few
files):
.IP
.EX
oans \-dr /foo
.EE
.PP
Dedupe a large tree, storing hashes so future runs are incremental.
Re\-running the same command only re\-hashes and re\-dedupes what
changed:
.IP
.EX
oans \-dr \-\-hashfile=foo.hash foo/
.EE
.PP
Replay the last run \[em] with no \f[I]file\f[R] arguments
\f[CR]oans\f[R] reuses the options, paths, and excludes saved in the
hashfile.
Ideal for cron:
.IP
.EX
oans \-\-hashfile=foo.hash
.EE
.PP
Add another directory to the set (this also becomes the new stored
config):
.IP
.EX
oans \-dr \-\-hashfile=foo.hash foo/ bar/
.EE
.PP
Preview what a run would dedupe, without changing anything (omit
\f[B]\-d\f[R]):
.IP
.EX
oans \-r foo/
.EE
.PP
Skip tiny files and a snapshot directory on a media server:
.IP
.EX
oans \-dr \-\-hashfile=media.hash \-\-min\-filesize=1M \[rs]
     \-\-exclude \[dq]/srv/media/.snapshots/*\[dq] /srv/media
.EE
.PP
Inspect a hashfile, watch savings over time, and export metrics:
.IP
.EX
oans \-\-stats   \-\-hashfile=foo.hash
oans \-\-history \-\-hashfile=foo.hash
oans \-\-json    \-\-hashfile=foo.hash | jq .reclaimed_total_bytes
.EE
.PP
Measure the best thread count for a NAS array (as root), storing it for
later runs:
.IP
.EX
sudo oans \-\-autotune \-\-hashfile=media.hash /srv/media
.EE
.SS Scheduled deduplication
Because the hashfile is self\-describing, a scheduled run only needs to
name it.
\f[CR]oans\f[R] ships systemd template units
(\f[CR]oans\[at].service\f[R] / \f[CR]oans\[at].timer\f[R], installed by
\f[CR]make install\-systemd\f[R]).
Set a job up once, then enable its timer \[em] the instance name is the
hashfile\[cq]s basename under \f[CR]/var/cache/oans\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
sudo oans \-dr \-\-hashfile=/var/cache/oans/media.hash /srv/media
sudo systemctl enable \-\-now oans\[at]media.timer
.EE
.PP
The timer then re\-deduplicates \f[CR]/srv/media\f[R] weekly, hashing
only what changed.
See \f[CR]docs/nas\-quickstart.md\f[R] in the source tree for the full
walkthrough.
.SH EXIT STATUS
\f[CR]oans\f[R] exits \f[B]0\f[R] on success.
A non\-zero status indicates a fatal error, such as invalid options or a
hashfile that could not be opened.
Note that individual per\-file dedupe failures (e.g.\ a file that
changed between scan and dedupe) are reported in the summary but do
\f[B]not\f[R] by themselves change the exit status; check the \f[I]Not
deduped\f[R] line, or run with \f[B]\-v\f[R], to detect them.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set (to any value), disables colored output, as
\f[B]\-\-no\-color\f[R] does.
.TP
\f[B]DUPEREMOVE_AUTOTUNE_MAX_FILES\f[R], \f[B]DUPEREMOVE_AUTOTUNE_MAX_BYTES\f[R], \f[B]DUPEREMOVE_AUTOTUNE_ROUNDS\f[R]
Bound the sample \f[B]\-\-autotune\f[R] reads (file count, total bytes,
and number of interleaved measurement rounds).
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]hashfile\f[R]
The SQLite database named by \f[B]\-\-hashfile\f[R].
Alongside it, SQLite may keep \f[CR]hashfile\-wal\f[R] and
\f[CR]hashfile\-shm\f[R] write\-ahead\-log sidecars; these are normal
and should not be deleted by hand.
.TP
\f[I]/var/cache/oans/\f[R]
Conventional location for scheduled\-job hashfiles used by the systemd
units (see \f[I]Scheduled deduplication\f[R]).
.SH NOTES
Deduplication is supported only on \f[B]btrfs\f[R] and \f[B]xfs\f[R].
.PP
On \f[B]xfs\f[R], \f[CR]oans\f[R] identifies the filesystem by its UUID.
This works unprivileged on Linux 6.4 and newer; on older kernels the
UUID lookup needs root, so run \f[CR]oans\f[R] with \f[B]sudo\f[R] there
(a scheduled root job is unaffected).
If the filesystem cannot be identified, \f[CR]oans\f[R] now stops with
an error instead of silently reporting nothing to do.
\f[B]btrfs\f[R] is unaffected.
.PP
The read\-only report modes (\f[B]\-\-stats\f[R], \f[B]\-\-history\f[R],
\f[B]\-\-json\f[R], \f[B]\-L\f[R]) open the hashfile read\-only and are
safe to run while another \f[CR]oans\f[R] process is scanning or
deduping the same hashfile: they show a consistent snapshot and never
write.
Running two \f[I]writing\f[R] invocations at once (two \f[B]\-d\f[R]
runs, or a \f[B]\-d\f[R] and an \f[B]\-R\f[R]) against the same hashfile
is \f[B]not\f[R] supported and may corrupt it.
.PP
Interrupting a run with Ctrl\-C is safe: the kernel owns the data, and
the hashfile is a transactional database, so you can stop and re\-run
without corrupting either.
Only a power loss can, in principle, damage a hashfile \[em] and never
your data.
.PP
Two logically identical files are not always deduped: \f[CR]oans\f[R]
works on extent boundaries, so files with the same content but a
different on\-disk extent layout may not match unless block\-level
matching is enabled with \f[B]\-\-dedupe\-options=partial\f[R].
.PP
\f[CR]oans\f[R] is offline, batch deduplication: you point it at
specific trees and run it on demand or on a timer.
This differs from \f[CR]bees\f[R], an always\-on daemon that
deduplicates the whole filesystem continuously, and from inline
filesystem dedupe such as ZFS, which maintains a permanent in\-RAM
dedupe table.
\f[CR]oans\f[R] keeps no such table and imposes no background cost
between runs.
